that allow species to coexist.

23:17.000 --> 23:19.000
It's not just that we want to say,

23:19.000 --> 23:21.000
because of environmental change,

23:21.000 --> 23:26.000
everyone has different levels of resources,

23:26.000 --> 23:28.000
so of course we can coexist.

23:28.000 --> 23:33.000
This kind of verbal argument is right.

23:33.000 --> 23:35.000
So this is the first one.

23:35.000 --> 23:39.000
I think it's a pretty eye-opening study.

23:39.000 --> 23:42.000
Then at the seminar,

23:42.000 --> 23:44.000
I also saw a few talks,

23:44.000 --> 23:46.000
so I tried to quantify

23:47.000 --> 23:52.000
why species can coexist in changing environments,

23:52.000 --> 23:58.000
and what is the mechanism behind their coexistence.

23:58.000 --> 24:00.000
Is everyone suitable for different environments?

24:00.000 --> 24:04.000
Or is the environment I affect affecting me?

24:04.000 --> 24:10.000
This is the first highlight I saw at this conference.

24:11.000 --> 24:14.000
I have a question.

24:14.000 --> 24:17.000
So you're showing this now,

24:17.000 --> 24:20.000
for example, there are two species of yellow and blue.

24:20.000 --> 24:21.000
Yellow and blue species.

24:21.000 --> 24:24.000
Both of them have a feature,

24:24.000 --> 24:27.000
which is that you can see the peak at each point.

24:27.000 --> 24:31.000
That is, the slope is very large.

24:31.000 --> 24:34.000
So it means that these two species themselves

24:34.000 --> 24:41.000
have a very small response time scale to change.

24:41.000 --> 24:43.000
Maybe less than a day.

24:43.000 --> 24:47.000
But if you look at the D-panel in the lower right corner,

24:47.000 --> 24:51.000
it's like external excitation.

24:51.000 --> 24:54.000
That is, their environment changes,

24:54.000 --> 24:57.000
their scale is ten days, five days,

24:57.000 --> 24:58.000
a few days, a few days, a few days.

24:58.000 --> 25:01.000
That's the width of black and white.

25:02.000 --> 25:07.000
So the time scale of the species system

25:07.000 --> 25:11.000
and the time scale of excitation are very different.

25:11.000 --> 25:14.000
So you can see this phenomenon very clearly.

25:14.000 --> 25:17.000
But if today the species must use

25:17.000 --> 25:19.000
about the same time,

25:19.000 --> 25:25.000
or even longer, to respond to external excitation,

25:25.000 --> 25:29.000
then the whole model will fail.

25:29.000 --> 25:32.000
Because it may not have time to reach the next state.

25:32.000 --> 25:34.000
The environment has changed again,

25:34.000 --> 25:36.000
and then it will collapse in the end.

25:36.000 --> 25:37.000
It's a mess.

25:37.000 --> 25:38.000
Yes, it's possible.

25:38.000 --> 25:40.000
So what I'm talking about now,

25:40.000 --> 25:42.000
this fluctuation-dependent thing,

25:42.000 --> 25:45.000
is actually what you're talking about.

25:45.000 --> 25:46.000
It's a relative concept.

25:46.000 --> 25:48.000
If the environment is changing,

25:48.000 --> 25:49.000
it must be fluctuation-dependent.

25:49.000 --> 25:57.000
It can be said that my own life cycle is very short.

25:57.000 --> 25:59.000
So even if the environment changes once a year,

25:59.000 --> 26:02.000
I have already given birth dozens of times a year.

26:02.000 --> 26:05.000
Yes, I have reproduced dozens of times.

26:05.000 --> 26:08.000
So the change in the environment is meaningless to me.

26:08.000 --> 26:10.000
So I just said that in a system,

26:10.000 --> 26:14.000
now we want to answer this question.

26:14.000 --> 26:16.000
Ecologists,

26:16.000 --> 26:19.000
the first difficult point is

26:19.000 --> 26:22.000
that we have to identify the change in the environment

26:22.000 --> 26:25.000
for the life cycle of my species.

26:25.000 --> 26:26.000
In terms of life cycle,

26:26.000 --> 26:28.000
is it dependent or independent?

26:28.000 --> 26:31.000
If it is dependent,

26:31.000 --> 26:33.000
if it is fluctuation-dependent,

26:33.000 --> 26:35.000
we can then ask

26:35.000 --> 26:40.000
which mechanism is it?

26:40.000 --> 26:43.000
Does this answer your question?

26:43.000 --> 26:44.000
Oh, thank you.

26:44.000 --> 26:46.000
Yes.

26:46.000 --> 26:48.000
Okay,

26:48.000 --> 26:51.000
next, like I just said,

26:51.000 --> 26:54.000
this is a very old question.

26:54.000 --> 26:56.000
It's so old that

26:56.000 --> 26:58.000
some people don't want to answer this question anymore.

26:58.000 --> 27:00.000
So everyone started to ask this question

27:00.000 --> 27:02.000
in another way.

27:02.000 --> 27:05.000
Now there are so many species in this environment.

27:05.000 --> 27:07.000
So then,

27:07.000 --> 27:09.000
the question just answered is

27:09.000 --> 27:10.000
why does this environment

27:10.000 --> 27:12.000
allow me to see so many species?

27:12.000 --> 27:14.000
But now,

27:14.000 --> 27:15.000
everyone may find it boring,

27:15.000 --> 27:16.000
so ask it the other way around.

27:16.000 --> 27:17.000
So many species,

27:17.000 --> 27:20.000
what impact will it have on this environment?

27:20.000 --> 27:22.000
This question

27:22.000 --> 27:23.000
or this question

27:23.000 --> 27:25.000
is actually not something that happened recently,

27:25.000 --> 27:27.000
but it suddenly became obvious.

27:27.000 --> 27:31.000
It probably started in the late 1990s.

27:31.000 --> 27:32.000
There was a person in Europe

27:32.000 --> 27:36.000
who did a project called Ecotron.

27:36.000 --> 27:37.000
In other words,

27:37.000 --> 27:40.000
it's probably like...

27:40.000 --> 27:41.000
I don't know if everyone knows

27:41.000 --> 27:42.000
that there is a kind of...

27:42.000 --> 27:43.000
Give you a glass ball,

27:43.000 --> 27:45.000
and then there is grass inside.

27:45.000 --> 27:46.000
There are different kinds of grass,

27:46.000 --> 27:50.000
and then there are some moss,

27:50.000 --> 27:51.000
something wet,

27:51.000 --> 27:53.000
like a planet.

27:53.000 --> 27:54.000
Ecotron is very similar to that concept.

27:54.000 --> 27:58.000
It's a microcosm.

27:58.000 --> 28:00.000
Their idea is that

28:00.000 --> 28:03.000
the more species there are in this microcosm,

28:03.000 --> 28:04.000
the more biomass I will see.

28:04.000 --> 28:10.000
I can see the more creatures in it.

28:10.000 --> 28:11.000
It started this

28:11.000 --> 28:18.000
Biodiversity Ecosystem Functioning Branch.

28:18.000 --> 28:20.000
Biodiversity

28:20.000 --> 28:23.000
How does it affect the function of this system?

28:23.000 --> 28:24.000
Function means

28:24.000 --> 28:26.000
what is the production volume of this system?

28:26.000 --> 28:30.000
How efficient is this system

28:30.000 --> 28:33.000
with the nutrient salt?

28:33.000 --> 28:34.000
The most famous one

28:34.000 --> 28:36.000
will be brought to everyone.

28:36.000 --> 28:39.000
It's in Minnesota.

28:39.000 --> 28:40.000
There is a person

28:40.000 --> 28:41.000
who is the first person

28:41.000 --> 28:43.000
to really do this large-scale experiment.

28:43.000 --> 28:47.000
You can see it in the picture on the left.

28:47.000 --> 28:48.000
It's called Seagull Creek.

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
It really digs a piece of land

28:51.000 --> 28:53.000
and plants this grass.

28:53.000 --> 28:58.000
You can see a plot.

28:58.000 --> 29:00.000
There may be five kinds of grass in this plot.

29:00.000 --> 29:01.000
There is one kind of grass in another plot.

29:01.000 --> 29:03.000
There are several kinds of grass in a plot.

29:03.000 --> 29:04.000
It goes down like this.

29:04.000 --> 29:06.000
Or in Germany,

29:06.000 --> 29:07.000
Jena Experiment

29:07.000 --> 29:08.000
also does similar things.

29:08.000 --> 29:09.000
There are different kinds of grass

29:09.000 --> 29:13.000
in each block.

29:14.000 --> 29:17.000
When I have a lot of grass,

29:17.000 --> 29:19.000
does this grass

29:19.000 --> 29:20.000
use different resources

29:20.000 --> 29:22.000
in order to survive?

29:22.000 --> 29:25.000
In total,

29:25.000 --> 29:26.000
I can take more resources

29:26.000 --> 29:29.000
from the environment.

29:29.000 --> 29:31.000
As I just said,

29:31.000 --> 29:33.000
there is a concept of a radish pit.

29:33.000 --> 29:35.000
The whole pit is full.

29:35.000 --> 29:38.000
We take a lot of resources

29:38.000 --> 29:40.000
from the system.

29:40.000 --> 29:44.000
A lot of biodiversity grows out of it.

29:44.000 --> 29:45.000
This kind of research

29:45.000 --> 29:49.000
has been done for more than 10 years.

29:49.000 --> 29:51.000
We have now discovered

29:51.000 --> 29:53.000
a general pattern.

29:53.000 --> 29:55.000
When we see a lot of species

29:55.000 --> 29:57.000
in an environment,

29:57.000 --> 29:59.000
when biodiversity increases,

29:59.000 --> 30:01.000
when X goes to the right,

30:01.000 --> 30:02.000
we see that those functions

30:02.000 --> 30:04.000
will increase.

30:04.000 --> 30:06.000
How much resources can we take away?

30:06.000 --> 30:09.000
How much biodiversity can we produce?

30:09.000 --> 30:11.000
We all see a function

30:11.000 --> 30:16.000
that increases but saturates.

30:16.000 --> 30:18.000
This is the knowledge we know now.

30:18.000 --> 30:19.000
However,

30:19.000 --> 30:21.000
the knowledge we have now

30:21.000 --> 30:26.000
is all based on grass experiment.

30:26.000 --> 30:27.000
This is the grass experiment

30:27.000 --> 30:29.000
I just showed here.

30:29.000 --> 30:31.000
We all plant grass

30:31.000 --> 30:33.000
or raise a certain

30:33.000 --> 30:36.000
nutrient-based organism.

30:36.000 --> 30:37.000
Then we find that

30:37.000 --> 30:41.000
the nutrient-based organism functions well.

30:41.000 --> 30:42.000
However,

30:42.000 --> 30:43.000
this is not enough.

30:43.000 --> 30:45.000
In our world,

30:45.000 --> 30:47.000
it is impossible to have only grass.

30:47.000 --> 30:48.000
At least there are humans.

30:48.000 --> 30:50.000
At least insects eat grass.

30:50.000 --> 30:51.000
Rabbits eat grass.

30:51.000 --> 30:52.000
Lions eat rabbits.

30:52.000 --> 30:55.000
There are many different kinds of life.

30:55.000 --> 30:56.000
Now,

30:56.000 --> 30:58.000
there are a few questions

30:58.000 --> 31:02.000
that ecologists want to continue to explore.

31:02.000 --> 31:03.000
The first is

31:03.000 --> 31:06.000
the function of these ecosystem.

31:06.000 --> 31:07.000
For example,

31:07.000 --> 31:09.000
the production of biomass, etc.

31:09.000 --> 31:11.000
Is it related to

31:11.000 --> 31:14.000
what we need in this world?

31:14.000 --> 31:16.000
This is the first one above.

31:16.000 --> 31:18.000
How do we put these functions

31:18.000 --> 31:20.000
and services

31:20.000 --> 31:22.000
I will talk about what service is later.

31:22.000 --> 31:25.000
Service is the function we need.

31:25.000 --> 31:27.000
How do we put these two things together?

31:27.000 --> 31:28.000
Otherwise, people will think that

31:28.000 --> 31:30.000
our ecological system is

31:30.000 --> 31:33.000
locked in a academic ivory tower.

31:33.000 --> 31:36.000
Purely understand the phenomenon of the natural environment

31:36.000 --> 31:37.000
and then it's over.

31:37.000 --> 31:38.000
No more.

31:38.000 --> 31:39.000
Everyone hopes that

31:39.000 --> 31:41.000
we ecologists can contribute to

31:41.000 --> 31:43.000
some changes in the environment, etc.

31:43.000 --> 31:46.000
This is the first

31:46.000 --> 31:48.000
ecologicalists

31:48.000 --> 31:51.000
want to continue to study.

31:51.000 --> 31:54.000
Next is what I just said.

31:54.000 --> 31:55.000
All the knowledge we learn now

31:55.000 --> 31:57.000
is very flat.

31:57.000 --> 31:59.000
Or the same nutrient class.

31:59.000 --> 32:00.000
But the natural environment

32:00.000 --> 32:02.000
is a very three-dimensional state.

32:02.000 --> 32:04.000
So should we

32:04.000 --> 32:05.000
put the natural environment

32:05.000 --> 32:08.000
into a very three-dimensional state?

32:08.000 --> 32:11.000
The third one is

32:11.000 --> 32:14.000
how can we predict accurately

32:14.000 --> 32:16.000
or accurately

32:16.000 --> 32:18.000
when the environment changes

32:18.000 --> 32:19.000
to reflect

32:19.000 --> 32:22.000
how many species will be left now.

32:22.000 --> 32:24.000
How many species will be left

32:24.000 --> 32:26.000
and how many functions

32:26.000 --> 32:28.000
will be left, etc.

32:28.000 --> 32:30.000
So these three are from

32:30.000 --> 32:33.000
Biodiversity Ecosystem Functioning.

32:33.000 --> 32:35.000
The three branches

32:35.000 --> 32:38.000
I think are ecological systems.

32:38.000 --> 32:41.000
I can't say it's obvious,

32:41.000 --> 32:43.000
but a lot of people are doing it.

32:43.000 --> 32:45.000
Now I'm going to talk about the first one.

32:45.000 --> 32:47.000
What is ecosystem services?

32:47.000 --> 32:49.000
These services mean

32:49.000 --> 32:51.000
all people

32:51.000 --> 32:52.000
live in this world

32:52.000 --> 32:54.000
and learn about these

32:54.000 --> 32:56.000
functions,

32:56.000 --> 32:57.000
patterns,

32:57.000 --> 33:00.000
all the things you need.

33:00.000 --> 33:01.000
And then,

33:01.000 --> 33:03.000
I remember it was the UN

33:03.000 --> 33:04.000
or something.

33:04.000 --> 33:08.000
The report of the Millennium Ecosystem Assessment.

33:08.000 --> 33:10.000
At that time, it was clearly defined

33:10.000 --> 33:13.000
that our current ecosystem

33:13.000 --> 33:15.000
is actually the whole earth.

33:15.000 --> 33:17.000
These services

33:17.000 --> 33:18.000
are provided to people.

33:18.000 --> 33:19.000
There are these four categories,

33:19.000 --> 33:21.000
supporting provisioning,

33:21.000 --> 33:23.000
regulation, and culture.

33:23.000 --> 33:25.000
The first few are easier to understand.

33:25.000 --> 33:27.000
Supporting services

33:27.000 --> 33:29.000
that support the operation of the earth.

33:29.000 --> 33:31.000
For example, the cycle of nutrients.

33:31.000 --> 33:33.000
You may have learned

33:33.000 --> 33:34.000
that in biology,

33:34.000 --> 33:36.000
we learn about the water cycle,

33:36.000 --> 33:37.000
the egg cycle, the carbon cycle,

33:37.000 --> 33:39.000
the carbon cycle, and so on.

33:39.000 --> 33:41.000
Or how much

33:41.000 --> 33:43.000
production

33:43.000 --> 33:45.000
can be used by us, etc.

33:45.000 --> 33:47.000
Then these will support

33:47.000 --> 33:49.000
how much food can we eat,

33:49.000 --> 33:51.000
the water cycle,

33:51.000 --> 33:52.000
because of the water cycle,

33:52.000 --> 33:53.000
how much clean water

33:53.000 --> 33:54.000
can be used by us.

33:54.000 --> 33:55.000
This is provisioning.

33:55.000 --> 33:57.000
Or when we want to manage

33:57.000 --> 33:58.000
a system,

33:58.000 --> 34:01.000
we don't want to have too many pests.

34:01.000 --> 34:04.000
We want to maximize,

34:04.000 --> 34:07.000
for example, maximize the number of corn.

34:07.000 --> 34:09.000
We don't want too many corn pests.

34:09.000 --> 34:11.000
The number of pest control

34:11.000 --> 34:15.000
is the regulation services.

34:15.000 --> 34:18.000
These three are relatively easy to understand.

34:18.000 --> 34:19.000
I think,

34:19.000 --> 34:21.000
and it is also now

34:21.000 --> 34:24.000
a big problem for ecologists.

34:24.000 --> 34:26.000
We call it cultural services.

34:26.000 --> 34:28.000
What I wrote here is

34:28.000 --> 34:30.000
you can think of everything

34:30.000 --> 34:32.000
related to culture.

34:32.000 --> 34:35.000
These are from the natural environment.

34:39.000 --> 34:41.000
You get these ideas.

34:41.000 --> 34:42.000
You get these inspirations.

34:42.000 --> 34:43.000
You get these education.

34:43.000 --> 34:44.000
You get to learn.

34:44.000 --> 34:46.000
But as long as it's related to the environment,

34:46.000 --> 34:48.000
it's not that kind of

34:48.000 --> 34:49.000
ugly.

34:49.000 --> 34:50.000
You don't have it.

34:50.000 --> 34:51.000
If you don't have it,

34:51.000 --> 34:52.000
you won't die.

34:52.000 --> 34:53.000
But you will live unhappily.

34:53.000 --> 34:56.000
These things are called culture.

34:56.000 --> 35:00.000
So some people say

35:00.000 --> 35:02.000
because nature is beautiful,

35:02.000 --> 35:03.000
it's too beautiful.

35:03.000 --> 35:05.000
So we can't maximize it.

35:05.000 --> 35:07.000
We can only rely on the beauty of our inner self

35:07.000 --> 35:10.000
to appreciate nature.

35:10.000 --> 35:12.000
Then there are other people who say

35:12.000 --> 35:14.000
that this is meaningless.

35:14.000 --> 35:16.000
I say what you say is beautiful.

35:16.000 --> 35:17.000
I can also say

35:17.000 --> 35:19.000
that there is nothing in the world that is the most beautiful.

35:19.000 --> 35:21.000
So how do we quantify

35:21.000 --> 35:23.000
the services of these ecosystems,

35:23.000 --> 35:26.000
especially the services of culture?

35:26.000 --> 35:28.000
This is something that some people

35:28.000 --> 35:31.000
are trying to figure out now.

35:31.000 --> 35:36.000
And that part of people

35:36.000 --> 35:39.000
includes a lot of economists.

35:39.000 --> 35:42.000
Because economists are very...

35:42.000 --> 35:44.000
I think

35:44.000 --> 35:46.000
they are very good at estimating

35:46.000 --> 35:48.000
the value of this thing in the market,

35:48.000 --> 35:50.000
and then how to trade it.

35:50.000 --> 35:51.000
So some people will think

35:51.000 --> 35:56.000
that we will quantify these services.

35:56.000 --> 35:57.000
For example,

35:57.000 --> 36:00.000
a piece of clean water

36:00.000 --> 36:03.000
is worth 2.5 million.

36:03.000 --> 36:06.000
Then a big clean swimming pool

36:06.000 --> 36:07.000
is worth 2.5 million.

36:07.000 --> 36:09.000
A big clean swimming pool

36:09.000 --> 36:10.000
is worth 10 million.

36:10.000 --> 36:12.000
I don't know.

36:12.000 --> 36:15.000
Just try to quantify it

36:15.000 --> 36:18.000
or find a way to...

